# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: catalytic-converter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] From 2020 to 2022, an organized criminal group stole and then resold catalytic converters through the United States.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The regional theft rings sent their stolen catalytic converters to DG Auto Parts in Freehold, New Jersey, who removed the precious metals from them and ground them into dust.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The precious metals were then sold to Dowa Metals and Mining America for refining, after which they were sent to Japan; these sales are believed to have generated approximately $545 million in revenue for DG Auto Parts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The investigation that led to the discovery of the interstate theft ring was prompted by a wave of catalytic converter thefts in the Oklahoma area in late 2020 and early 2021, with similar rises across the United States.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] By September, a team of investigators had linked Curtis Cores with DG Auto Parts, which was owned by Navin and Tinu Khanna.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] On November 2, police executed simultaneous search warrants across the US on over 32 sites, resulting in 21 arrests in 5 states.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The dismantling of the interstate theft ring was described as the first national takedown of a catalytic converter theft ring by the Department of Justice.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Following the dismantling of the interstate theft ring, the theft of catalytic converters dropped dramatically.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] According to the National Insurance Crime Bureau, over 5,000 catalytic converter thefts were reported per month in 2022.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In the first nine months of 2023, there were 2,675 catalytic converter thefts reported per month.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A catalytic converter is a typically oblong-shaped vehicle emissions control device that makes up part of an automobile's exhaust system.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The catalytic converter accelerates a chemical reaction using heat and precious metals contained within the device, such as platinum, rhodium, and palladium (PRP), to transform toxic engine exhaust gases into less-toxic pollutants and other non-polluting gases.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Catalytic converters became mandatory in American automobiles following the Clean Air Act of 1975, but are easy to surreptitiously remove from vehicles.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] From 2001 to 2021, the price of PRP rose dramatically: platinum rose from $530 per ounce to about $1100 ($964.00 to $1,307, adjusted for inflation).
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] This led to an epidemic of thefts targeting the device for sale to scrap dealers.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In a 2021 report, the NICB stated that "in 2018, there were 1,298 catalytic converter thefts reported.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Initially, the operation of the theft scheme appeared a continuation of this baseline trend.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In the 2023 report, the NCIB stated that "based on insurance claims, thefts of catalytic converters increased significantly from 2020 through 2022".
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In addition, there were 16,660 insurance claims for catalytic converter thefts in 2020, a number that had increased to 64,701 by 2022.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The report also stated that the highest rate for catalytic converter theft claims between 2020 and 2022 was California, with 24,102 thefts reported to insurers.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In 2022 alone, an average of 1,600 catalytic converters were reported stolen each month in California.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Dowa Holdings is a precious metals refiner that began in 1884 as a mining operation in the town of Kosaka, Akita Prefecture.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The company specialized in mining kuroko ore, a rare black volcanic deposit found only in Japan and primarily in Akita Prefecture in the Hokuroku Basin.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Dowa expanded its domestic mining operations during the early 20th century and began exploring international opportunities for expansion in the 1940s.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] By 1990 Kosaka Mine had closed and by 1994 Dowa's domestic operations in Japan were suspended "due to economic changes and the depletion of ore".
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In 2015, Dowa Holdings established Dowa Metals & Mining America, starting their operations at a refinery in Burlington, New Jersey, some time after.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] After Dowa evaluated the PRP dust that it received, it would pay its suppliers and refine the dust into chunks in their refinery.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] It is unknown as to whether Dowa Metals & Mining America performed any form of vetting on DG Auto Parts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The chunks would then be shipped to Tanaka Precious Metals in Akita, where they would be prepared for sale.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Between 2018 and 2022, Tanaka Precious Metals' annual revenue increased by approximately 20% to $288 million.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Navin and his brother, Tinu Khanna, were first-generation immigrants from India.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Their older brothers owned and operated a wrecking yard and, after working there for a few years, Navin and Tinu began their own business ventures.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In 2016 they began a rubber disposal business, in 2018 they began a recycling business and in 2019 they also started a company in the auto wrecking industry under the name DG Auto Wreckers.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] According to an interview performed by Navin with ACE Finance, none of their prior endeavors succeeded until DG Auto Wreckers; this success was due to finding Dowa Metals & Mining America.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A subpoena into the brothers' bank records corroborated the interview: between March 2021 and April 2022, a total of $224 million was transferred by Dowa into a single account used by DG Auto Parts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A further $175 million was discovered on another account.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] DG Auto Wreckers traded in used car parts, including catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Initially, the business remained small, with sellers bringing in small loads from across New Jersey.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] However, when the COVID-19 pandemic began, the prices of PRP metals rose drastically.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In December 2019, rhodium cost $6,000 per ounce and by March 2021, the price rose to $21,000 per ounce, with platinum and palladium seeing similar rises.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The brothers incorporated the business as DG Auto Parts in February 2020 and moved to the Freehold, New Jersey, site.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] They decided to focus on catalytic converter recycling and bought four decanning machines.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] These machines break apart the catalytic converters and demolish the cores into dust, which was then collected and sent to Dowa's refinery in Burlington, New Jersey.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] That year, DG Auto Parts bought a site in Emporia, Virginia, which they named DG Auto South, and began partnering with converter businesses across the US, including Curtis Cores.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A neighboring business' manager said "people would come with tractor trailers and drop them off.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Dumpsters full of cat[alytic converter]s.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] They were working 24 hours." Investigations would later reveal that DG Auto Parts did not care whether their supplies were obtained legally.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The codes on catalytic converters identify the make, model and place of origin of catalytic converters, which in turn identify their value, due to variation in state emission laws.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] As an example, GD3 EA6 denotes a Toyota Prius manufactured between 2004 and 2009; at the peak of the PRP metal prices, its high palladium content could sell for more than $1,800.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] As the profits grew, DG Auto Parts began making advance payments in the millions to their largest suppliers, including Curtis Cores, so that they too could provide their suppliers with the highest prices to maximize the supply of catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The investigation that led to the discovery of the theft ring began in late 2020 and early 2021, when a wave of catalytic converter thefts struck the Tulsa, Oklahoma area.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Police began arresting "cutters", low-level criminals responsible for stealing catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The police then attempted to get the cutters to reveal who they were selling to.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] According to the cutters, one such person was Steven Low Sr., an insurance agent and dealer in catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In May 2021, GPS tracked Low's vehicle to an automobile recycling warehouse on Oklahoma State Highway 51 in Broken Arrow.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The officers then called a lieutenant, their liaison with the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) regarding the theft wave.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Questioned on where the catalytic converters came from, Curtis claimed that his automobile recycling business which had opened in January 2021, Curtis Cores, had obtained them legally.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Curtis and his passenger were then arrested for possession of drugs and an unpermitted firearm.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] To legally possess the catalytic converters, Curtis needed a scrap metal license, which Curtis did not possess; however, he said that his father had submitted an application for the permit.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] It was later discovered that, while he was in jail, he made a recorded phone call in which he asked his parents to remove incriminating objects from the warehouse.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Curtis pleaded guilty or no contest in the Tulsa County District Court to the drug and firearm charges, receiving a three-year deferred sentence.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] After releasing Curtis on bail, police obtained a search warrant regarding Curtis' seized phone and iPad.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] On these devices, they discovered a Facebook messaging group including Curtis, a man called Navin Khanna and another called Adam Sharkey.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] By September, a team of investigators, led by Brad Staggs and Kansas Core, had identified that the stolen catalytic converters were being transported from across the US to a Freehold, New Jersey, company called DG Auto Parts where the cores were extracted and then shipped overseas.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In December, Kansas Core had obtained a warrant to place a 24-hour surveillance camera on a pole outside Curtis Cores.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Vehicles arrived daily, sometimes hourly, full of catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Curtis and his employees would then unload the converters, inspect them, and pay cash.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Then the converters would be packed into cardboard boxes, wrapped in plastic and loaded onto pallets for transport.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The business handled between 5,000 and 6,000 catalytic converters per week.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] These catalytic converters would then be transported either directly to DG Auto Parts or to Adam, an intermediary in New York.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Several weeks after Kansas Core gained the warrant to surveil Curtis Cores, he gained a search warrant for Curtis's Facebook account.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Looking through his account, they—alongside a team associated with the Homeland Security Investigations (HSI) division in Tulsa—traced the development of the trafficking ring.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Curtis had started working at Green Country Auto Core part-time three years before his arrest.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Between May and August 2020, Curtis found DG Auto Parts and put the owner, Navin Khanna, in contact with Edwards.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Edwards would later say of Navin "I didn't deal with that guy [Navin Khanna] much.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Curtis dealt with him...I did talk to the guy—just kind of rubbed me the wrong way." Court documents would later reveal that Green Country Auto Core had sold approximately $2 million worth of catalytic converters to them.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In late 2020, Curtis told Edwards that he would be starting his own business and that he would be bringing DG Auto Parts with him.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Edwards later said of this "I felt I wasted a lot of time on him, showing him the business.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Would've been nice to have a little warning, couple of weeks at least.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Kansas Core and other investigators started filing for more warrants: intercepting calls made to and from Curtis's phone, tracking the locations of his employees' phones, and monitoring their Facebook accounts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Another warrant authorized a pole camera outside Curtis's home, where he lived with his wife, on a large plot of land owned by his in-laws.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Since Curtis Cores had received stolen catalytic converters, he could be prosecuted in federal court.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A regular delivery arrived from Houston, Texas, where the sellers specialized in "torpedo"-type catalytic converters – named for their distinctive shape – extracted from Toyota Tacoma and Tundra pickup trucks.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] On March 31, 2022, in Houston, off-duty sheriff's deputy Darren Almendarez was grabbing groceries with his wife, and parked their Toyota Tundra outside of a Joe V's Smart Shop north of the city.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Leaving the store, Almendarez noticed that a black Nissan Altima had backed up to his vehicle.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Almendarez had worked in an auto theft unit in the Harris County Sheriff's Office and recognized an apparent catalytic converter theft in progress.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] As he approached, two men clambered out from under his truck and into the Altima, and he told his wife to run away and call the police.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The driver of the Altima raised a handgun; Almendarez drew his own; in the ensuing shootout, Almendarez and two men inside the Altima were shot; and then the men fled.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Almendarez was rushed to Houston Northwest Hospital, where he was pronounced dead.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Not long after, Joshua Stewart and Fredarius Clark arrived at the same hospital seeking treatment for gunshot wounds.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Following treatment, they were taken into custody.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A third suspect, Fredrick Tardy, was arrested the following day.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Houston police suspected that the three men delivered their stolen goods into a supply chain running through Tulsa.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A week after Almendarez's death, the pole camera monitoring Curtis Cores recorded a black GMC pickup truck with Texas license plates pulling a U-Haul trailer of catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The truck was traced back to Isaac Castillo, a Houston resident.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Houston police had already stopped Castillo in February 2022, when he was driving a pickup carrying catalytic converters, discovering an unlicensed firearm and $25,000 in cash.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Upon his return to Texas, police stopped Castillo again.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Searching the truck, police discovered a box containing $206,000 in cash.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Castillo continued to deny any wrongdoing, claiming that the money was a result of selling scrap in Oklahoma.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] However, police continued to investigate, and identified Castillo as a member of a "Ley Road gang".
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Houston police and the Houston HSI alleged that the three men accused of Almendarez's death had been using the Ley Road gang and another gang as fences for the catalytic converters they stole.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] At the time, Castillo was not among those detained.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The police obtained a warrant to locate his phone, which placed him at Curtis Cores making another delivery.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Shortly after leaving, Castillo was stopped by police for a third time, and this time arrested.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Castillo would later tell investigators that Curtis kept $500,000 in his desk drawer and knew the catalytic converters he obtained and sold were stolen.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] When interviewed, one of the gang's leaders told police that Curtis had instructed him as to what vehicles to steal from.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] According to court documents, Theodore Nicholas Papouloglou incorporated DG Auto South in Emporia, Virginia, in November 2020.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He incorporated the business as a "scrap metal business" and a "money transmission business".
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Neither he nor the business were registered as a money transmitting business, as required by the Department of the Treasury and by Virginia laws.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Papouloglou received over $12.2 million in wired payments from DG Auto Parts between 2020 and 2021.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He bought stolen catalytic converters from thieves in the area, which would then be transported to DG Auto Parts for shipment to Dowa.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He also helped DG Auto Parts to buy catalytic converters from other sellers across state lines, including from Texas and Oklahoma, paying for these in bulk cash payments, with the total paid out by Papouloglou being at least $6.6 million.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Despite this income, he paid no taxes on it during that time frame.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A federal indictment was filed on March 19, 2024, including four counts; two of evasion of income tax assessments, one of conspiracy to transfer, receive, conceal and sell stolen goods and one of operating an unlicensed money transmitting business.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He pleaded not guilty to all counts the following day, however he later plead guilty to the first count of evasion of income tax assessments and to the count of conspiracy to transfer, receive, conceal and sell stolen goods on August 20 that year.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] On March 12, 2025, he was sentenced to two years and three months in prison.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] According to an indictment from July 2022, Tanner Hellbusch, who bought and resold cars and their components, began stealing catalytic converters sometime prior to February 2021.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He was identified as a major local source of stolen catalytic converters, either stealing them himself or buying them from thieves and selling them on.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] At the time he lived with Jerrica Oga-Garo, his new fiancée, in Oak Hills, Beaverton, Oregon; he and his fiancée operated the business from their home, using the property to store catalytic converters and meet with buyers.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Hellbusch placed advertisements on Facebook Marketplace looking for new suppliers.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In 2021, Oregon passed a law requiring that scrap metal businesses make a record of all catalytic converter purchases, including the vehicle identification number that they came from.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] This law also made it illegal to perform these transactions with cash.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] This led Hellbusch to try and find other buyers, leading him to begin selling catalytic converters through Brennan Doyle.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Doyle began his own business buying stolen catalytic converters from across the Western US in early 2021, with Hellbusch becoming one of his major suppliers.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Doyle then found Adam Sharkey, after which he bought a warehouse in Aurora, Oregon, recruiting some of his friends to help him run the business.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Jenna Wilson, with whom he had an intermittent relationship with, helped with the accounting, while Benjamin Jamison (who Doyle had known since high school) met with prospective buyers and handled transactions.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] By mid–2022, Brennan Doyle and Benjamin Jamison moved to a lakefront rental property on South Shore Boulevard, Lake Oswego, Oregon.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The property was a two-bedroom house, costing $5,000 a month to rent.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] They also bought a $15,000 speedboat and held parties at the house.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] An officer from the Beaverton Police Department and a detective from Clackamas County, Oregon, provided information that pointed towards Hellbusch being a major source of stolen catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Based on this, the Beaverton Police Department began an investigation into the theft ring.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] By mid–2022, two dozen officers from various entities were surveilling the Lake Oswego property and the Aurora warehouse, however, the department had difficulties proving that Doyle knew he was receiving stolen catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In an effort to help prove this, the Oregon Department of Justice allowed the Beaverton Police Department to wiretap four phones, including Doyle's.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Using these wiretaps and freight receipts, detectives unravelled the organisation and discovered Doyle's connection to Adam Sharkey.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The wiretaps were so successful because of how indiscreet Doyle was with his dealings, he often called his friends to discuss the shipping of catalytic converters, which included who was performing the deliveries and what they contained.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Over mid–2022, Phillip Kearney, then assistant special agent in charge at the Oregon Department of Justice, began seizing the ring's assets and intercepting their wire transfers.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Another alleged accomplice of Doyle, his childhood friend Casey Smith, complained online about how he was unable to access his bank account, losing access to $130,000.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Later, Doyle and his alleged accomplices met to discuss whether their accounts had been frozen or whether the incidents were coincidences, and to discuss ways to get around their issues, unaware that Kearney had followed them.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A SWAT team raided Hellbusch's house while police raided the Lake Oswego property and the Aurora warehouse on August 3, 2022, discovering almost $40,000 in cash in Doyle's bedroom and 3,000 catalytic converters at the warehouse.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] 14 people were indicted by a grand jury, almost all of which were charged with various crimes including racketeering, theft and money laundering.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Among them, Wilson, Jamison, Hellbusch and Oga-Garo were charged with theft and racketeering while Smith was charged with racketeering.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Doyle was charged with 90 counts relating to aggravated theft, money laundering, racketeering and unlawfully receiving stolen metal, with Hellbusch facing 25 counts under similar charges.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Despite the fact that Operation Heavy Metal was ongoing at the time, the investigation did not track catalytic converter thefts further than connecting the Sharkey's to the interstate theft ring, thus missing the connection to Oregon.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Downpipe Depot and Recycling was a business owned by Alexander Kolitsas in East Hartford and Wolcott, Connecticut that operated between January 2021 and June 2022.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] They operated similarly to the other groups, buying catalytic converters from thieves before transporting and selling them to DG Auto Parts and an unnamed recycling business in New York, sometimes receiving over $200,000 per sale.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He was assisted by Bryant Bermudez, who started there around November 2021.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] One of the thieves, Yanquee Rodriguez, was paid $411,845 between January 2021 and May 2022, for supplying stolen catalytic converters to Downpipe Depot and Recycling; records seized during the investigation showed that he was their largest supplier.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Other thieves included in the network were Roberto Alicea, Francisco Ayala, Theodore Roosevelt Owens, Marvin Figueroa and Michael Almodovar.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In total, Kolitsas paid thieves $3,345,675 for stolen catalytic converters between January 26 and May 31, 2022.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] According to court documents, Kolitsas and Bermudez stored firearms at Downpipe Depot and Recycling and Kolitsas' home.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] During the investigation, it was revealed that Almodovar had sold approximately $34,000 of stolen catalytic converters to Downpipe Depot and Recycling; in a post on his social media, he described attacking a witness with a knife before stealing a catalytic converter.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Several search warrants were executed on June 1, 2022, resulting in the seizure of five firearms, $47,000 from Kolitsas, $20,000 from Bermudez, approximately $8,000 from Downpipe Depot and Recycling and several vehicles.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A federal indictment for one count of conspiracy to transport stolen property and one or more counts of interstate transportation of stolen property was passed down for Kolitsas, Bermudez, Alicea, Ayala and Owens on August 16, 2022.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Kolitsas was further indicted for promotional money laundering, two counts of engaging in monetary transactions with proceeds of specified unlawful activity, and possession of firearms by an unlawful drug user or addict.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Bermudez and Alicea were arrested on 23 August, Ayala was in state custody and Owens was in federal custody for unrelated offences.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Kolitsas turned himself in on August 24.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Alicea pleaded guilty on June 23, 2023, with sentencing scheduled for September 5.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A superseding indictment was passed down in November 2023 including Kolitsas, Rodriguez, Figueroa and Almodovar.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Figueroa and Rodriguez were arrested on November 15, 2023.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Figueroa pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit interstate transportation of stolen property and interstate transportation of stolen property on October 9, 2024, and was sentenced to 14 months federal imprisonment on 8 April 2025 to be followed by three years of probation.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Rodriguez pleaded guilty to one count of conspiracy to commit interstate transportation of stolen property and one count of interstate transportation of stolen property on June 26, 2024.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He was sentenced on February 20, 2025, to 15 months imprisonment followed by three years of probation.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Almodovar was arrested and later sentenced in federal court to 14 months imprisonment.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Kolitsas pleaded guilty to one count of conspiracy to commit interstate transportation of stolen property and one count of promotional money laundering on October 7, 2024.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He was released on a $150,000 bond and sentenced on 21 April the following year to five years imprisonment followed by two years probation.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He was ordered to report to prison on July 14.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Ayala pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit interstate transportation of stolen property and interstate transportation of stolen property on April 4, 2023, with sentencing scheduled for July 13 that year.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Bermudez pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit interstate transportation of stolen property and three counts of interstate transportation of stolen property on April 10.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] His sentencing was scheduled for July 12 that year, though was later postponed until 15 May 2025.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He was fined $20,000 and ordered to perform 300 hours of community service over three years of probation.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Following a rise in catalytic converter thefts in Weld County, Colorado, Weld County Sherriff's Office (WCSO) began investigating in 2021.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] This later led police to Elevation Auto Core in Brighton, Colorado.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In 2022, the WCSO was contacted by the Colorado Bureau of Investigation and HSI.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The investigation expanded to the state and federal level because Elevation Auto Core was a part of the larger theft ring, including a business in Las Vegas, Nevada.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Police tracked one of Curtis's employees, Shane Minnick, to Elevation Auto Core on May 2, 2022, after which they discovered that the employee would soon be traveling back to Tulsa.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Minnick was stopped at the airport, where a cash-sniffing dog alerted officers to his bag, which contained $500,000 in cash.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Minnick signed the money over to the police.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] According to arrest papers in the case, undercover officers and confidential informants wearing cameras found they could walk in and easily sell "obviously stolen catalytic converters".
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Despite changes to Colorado law requiring identification and other personal information to be collected in the sale of catalytic converters, little to no questions were asked in three different sting operations.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The catalytic converters were then (similar to the Curtis Cores operation) packaged and placed onto pallets to be transported out of state (most of which were sent to the "east coast" or overseas) or decanned on-site.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Six men were taken into custody in both Colorado and Nevada on December 13, 2022, charged with violations of the Colorado Organized Crime Control Act, Colorado tax laws, theft, and money laundering.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The four bought batches of catalytic converters in several states in late 2021, one of which had an Apple AirTag inside of it.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] This allowed investigators to track the catalytic converter as it was transported in a shipment worth $425,000 to New York.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In August 2022, Moo allegedly traded stolen catalytic converters for several AR-15 style rifles and a firearm with an auto sear.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] To maintain the image of a legitimate business in case of an audit or investigation, they also bought scrap cars from sellers or an auction.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In order to conceal payments, Johnson also sometimes directed the payments to his father, grandmother and a real estate company.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In total, they received approximately $21 million in payments using wire transfers, cash, cheques or a combination of methods; $19 million of this was solely across state lines.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Prosecutors said that the group took multiple trips to a buyer in New Jersey in 2021 before flying back to Minnesota, with at least three of these trips netting them a profit of nearly $500,000.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Prior to Kotten's arrest, several search warrants relating to the ring were executed in November 2022 by the Sleepy Eye Police Department and the Brown County Sheriff's Office.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He was arrested on November 2 during a federal search warrant where two stolen vehicles were discovered.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] "Hundreds" of catalytic converters were seized from properties in Hutchinson, Sleepy Eye, St.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Paul and Madison Lake alongside trucks, tools and over $500,000.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The four were charged on October 18, 2023, for conspiracy to transport stolen property across state lines, with all four making their first appearances at a federal courthouse in St.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Kotten and Johnson were further charged with conspiracy to commit money laundering and false statements to a financial institution, while Moo was charged with possession of an automatic firearm.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] All four originally pleaded guilty, however on December 10, 2024, Kotten pleaded guilty to one count of conspiracy to transport stolen goods across state lines.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In November that year, two other members of the ring pleaded guilty to conspiracy and gun crimes.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] On May 2, 2019, Vang Auto Core LLC was started by Tou Vang, who was joined soon after by his brother, Andrew Vang.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] On May 31, Tou was arrested for the theft of a catalytic converter from a Prius.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Between May 2 and October 1 that year, Vang Auto Core was already in contact with DG Auto Parts, with their first transaction occurring on October 1.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In the following three months, the Vangs withdrew approximately $460,000 in $10,000 increments.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] This is likely due to the Bank Secrecy Act, a law requiring banks to report transactions larger than $10,000 to the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In September 2020, a Prius owner in Davis, California, discovered that their catalytic converter had been stolen.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Investigation into the theft uncovered footage recorded by a vehicle on the same street, which showed a vehicle stopping near the Prius during the night, much like how the thieves had stopped behind Almendarez's vehicle in Houston.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The vehicle and its owner were identified, and surveillance began.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The following month, police stopped the vehicle and, upon searching it, discovered a number of catalytic converters inside.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Two men were arrested in connection with this, Dao Xiong and Shaneel Lal.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Prosecutors charged the two men with the theft of 64 catalytic converters in eight northern California counties.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] During surveillance, investigators observed the two men casing neighborhoods during the day, only to return by night to steal catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Investigators also tracked Xiong to the Vangs home on Meadowgate Drive, Sacramento.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The police acquired a search warrant for a phone confiscated from a known cutter in August 2020.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In it, they discovered discussions between the cutter and a man called Choy Saeteurn, a mechanic based in Sacramento, regarding catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Police then acquired a search warrant for Saeteurn's Facebook account.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] With this search warrant, police discovered that on September 3, 2020, Tou and Saeteurn had a text conversation about Saeteurn returning to buying and selling catalytic converters, saying that he was doing so discreetly.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Prosecutors later alleged that Tou was buying discreetly due to his prior arrest in 2019.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] By September 2020 however, he was already under investigation for the interstate trafficking of catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Navin communicated with Saeteurn a week later on September 10 about a need for more "Prius", referring to Toyota Priuses and their catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In this conversation, he referred to Tou directly.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The next day, Navin communicated with Saeteurn about Tou shipping 300 catalytic converters to DG Auto Parts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Bank records later showed that DG Auto Parts had paid Vang Auto Core $400,000 for the catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In April 2021, shipping manifests showed that Vang Auto Core had shipped two crates weighing a combined 4,370 pounds (1,980 kilograms) to DG Auto Parts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In the two weeks following, DG Auto Parts paid Vang Auto Core a further $975,000.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Police began using a confidential informant to sell catalytic converters to the Vangs at their house some time between April and May 2021.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Between then and August that year, the informant made five sales of between two or three catalytic converters at a time.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] On one occasion, the informant told the Vangs that he had stolen one from a Prius that he'd previously targeted.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] According to police, many of the cutters that sold to the Vangs were also related to the Tiny Rascal Gang (TRG).
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The TRG was founded in 1981 in Long Beach, California by Cambodian refugees seeking protection from neighboring gangs.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Due to this and the fact the Vangs operated the business from home, the Vangs were known to keep at least five firearms in their house and more than 1,300 rounds of ammunition.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] One of the Vangs' neighbors, Joe McElroy, came back from work some time in November 2021, finding the street cordoned off by police; there was yellow crime tape surrounding the Vangs house and a tarp covering a corpse on the driveway.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Upon asking around, he discovered that Andrew Vang had shot a burglar who had broken into their house.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Not long after, he witnessed a "stream" of police entering the house with dogs and sledgehammers.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] McElroy later said of this "Cops come over and fucked up the whole house...Just ransacked it.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] They destroyed it." The Vangs moved out within a few days, with the damage said to have taken approximately eight months to repair.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Due to the nature of the Vangs' operation, investigators speculated that the perpetrators knew about their business and targeted their home expecting to find money there.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Andrew was not charged for the shooting, as the shooting was deemed to have been self defense.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] When the Vangs left their home, they looked to DG Auto Parts to help them.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In December 2021, the Khanna brothers paid approximately $1.2 million for a house in northern Sacramento on their behalf.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] By the second quarter of 2022, investigators already suspected that DG Auto Parts was the hub for the sale of stolen catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] A Wyandotte Nation Tribal Police Department officer stopped a rental truck on May 8, 2022.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] During the stop a detection dog was used to search the vehicle and it indicated that it had found something.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] It was discovered that the vehicle was carrying three pallets of catalytic converters and approximately $1.3 million in cash.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The driver, Robert Sharkey, "provided various mixed narratives to the purpose of his trip, or the source of the catalytic converters and money." The name Sharkey was already known to police in Tulsa due to his son, Adam Sharkey, DG Auto Parts' associate in New York.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] According to police, the money had originated from DG Auto Parts and approximately $290,000 was destined for Curtis Cores.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Robert was allegedly transferring money to another intermediary, Martynas Macerauskas, in Amarillo, Texas.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Martynas was the owner of M&M Auto, a business in Clarendon, Texas who partnered with DG Auto Parts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Two days after Robert Sharkey was stopped, Martynas' wife, Kristina, was stopped in Texas with approximately $1.2 million in her vehicle; she told police that she had driven it from DG Auto Parts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In a search of M&M Auto, police found 30 catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In total, the Macerauskas' received more than $6 million from DG Auto Parts for catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] That same day, the pole camera surveilling Curtis Cores recorded Curtis's employees awaiting Robert's arrival.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] At approximately 3 a.m., Curtis was informed that Robert had been stopped and that the money had been seized.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Two days after Robert Sharkey was stopped, Curtis flew to Newark Liberty International Airport and drove to DG Auto Parts while being followed by investigators.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] When he left, he was carrying approximately $1 million in bags which he then drove back to Oklahoma.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Curtis did become more careful upon returning after the raids against the Connecticut group and the Ley Road gang out of concern that police would link them back to him.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He altered how he would buy stolen goods, refused to travel with large sums of money and would routinely check with his wife to ensure the money stashed around their property was safe.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] When federal investigators later obtained a wiretap for an employee of DG Auto Parts, they recorded Navin on August 5 telling him that traveling with money was too risky and that the police were "busting everybody".
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] An August drop in PRP prices, particularly palladium, strained DG Auto Parts' finances.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] One buyer threatened to sue the company for stealing data from the pricing app.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] There were accusations on their Facebook page that the brothers offered large sums of money for large quantities of catalytic converters and then refused to pay.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In September 2022, DG Auto Parts announced that it had secured funding out of its financial difficulties with private investment firm Barrett Edge, who praised the Khanna brothers as "consummate professionals".
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Meanwhile, investigators sent confidential informants to DG Auto Parts for months to sell catalytic converters, all the while emphasizing that they were stolen.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In a Facebook message, Navin said, "every cat in Cali [is] stolen I can promise you that".
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Federal indictments later alleged that on September 1, a confidential informant claimed that their cousin worked in a Toyota warehouse and that they could steal catalytic converters and "bricks" (cores that had not yet been put into catalytic converters) from the Priuses stored there.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The brothers agreed to the plan, paying $259,000 for 402 bricks and 98 catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] By the third quarter of 2022, the investigation into the interstate catalytic converter theft ring was reaching its conclusion.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Now nicknamed Operation Heavy Metal, the investigation had grown to include over 70 local and federal agencies.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] By chance, investigators in Operation Heavy Metal discovered the investigation into the Vang family; as such, the investigation was merged into Operation Heavy Metal.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] It was later discovered that Vang Auto Core had sold over $38 million of catalytic converters to DG Auto Parts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The case had become so large that agents from multiple different agencies had to meet together in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, to coordinate the final stages of the investigation.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] On the morning of November 2, the owner of a store adjacent to Curtis Cores, Jeremy Jones of JT Auto, was in his office grabbing a cup of coffee when he witnessed the police storming into Curtis Cores.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] He later said of the day, "I look out the window and something caught my eye—it was like a SWAT team.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] There's guys with assault rifles and military gear." Curtis, who had left shortly before the raid, returned not long after and was arrested.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Six of his partners and employees and his wife were arrested the same day.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Police used a helicopter and officers riding all-terrain vehicles to search unsuccessfully for the money stashed on his wife's family's land where he and his wife lived.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Staggs said of this "he probably has money hidden somewhere that we'll never find".
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Curtis admitted in an August 2025 plea agreement that he had received approximately $16 million from DG Auto Parts between March 2021 and October 2022 for the shipment of catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Simultaneously across the US, police executed more than 32 search warrants on locations used by the various organizations involved in the ring, seizing "homes, bank accounts, cash, and luxury vehicles", among other assets, which were valued at "tens of millions of dollars".
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] In total, 21 arrests were made in five states.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Seven people associated with DG Auto Parts were among those who were arrested, six of whom had been involved in decanning and selling the metals to refineries.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] The Sharkeys gained approximately $45 million from the sale of stolen catalytic converters to DG Auto Parts and were arrested in New York.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Curtis received approximately $500,000 from Capital Cores, a company operated by Adam in Long Island, New York.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Over the course of their investigation, police discovered that Dowa Metals & Mining America had paid $545 million in revenue to DG Auto Parts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Prosecutors said that of the approximately $25 million withdrawn from this sum by the Khannas, only $150,000 was recovered.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] As such, the Khannas were deemed to be a flight risk if released on bail.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Despite surveillance and bank records proving Dowa to be the source of DG Auto Parts' money, the company's name was withheld during the indictments against Curtis and the Khannas, only being referred to as an unindicted co-conspirator.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p01] Lauren Horwood, a spokesperson for the Eastern District of California US Attorneys Office, described Operation Heavy Metal as the first national takedown of a catalytic converter theft ring by the Department of Justice.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] Staggs stated that Operation Heavy Metal had drastically cut the rate of catalytic converter thefts, saying "in the four months prior to that national takedown day, there were 250 reports of catalytic converter theft.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] In the four months after, there were 38." According to the NICB, by 2023 reports of catalytic converter thefts had declined significantly nationwide.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] In the first nine months of 2023, there were 2,675 catalytic converter thefts reported per month, down from over 5,000 in 2022.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] A similar fall was registered in Houston, in March 2022 there were 1,200 catalytic converter thefts reported and on March 31 Deputy Almendarez was killed.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The following month the number of reports dropped to approximately 950, falling gradually to 900 reports by July 2022.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] On July 28 the Ley Road Gang was raided, with the number of reports falling to approximately 400 by the end of the year.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The number of reports stayed steady until May 29 that year, which was when Senate Bill 224, known as the Deputy Darren Almendarez Act, became effective.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The act aimed to "provide a framework of offenses, penalties and enhancements", with one of the enhancements being that if a firearm was used in the theft of a catalytic converter, the charge would become a felony.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] From then, the amount of reports fell gradually to almost zero by February 2024.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The government was seeking forfeiture of approximately $545 million in connection with the case; it is unclear whether they received this amount during the search and seizure efforts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] Robert's charges were reduced to misprision of a felony on 5 December 2024.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] Both pleaded guilty in a federal court in Tulsa on December 9, 2024, with Adam pleading guilty to one count of conspiracy and receiving a mandatory maximum of five years imprisonment.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] As a part of their plea agreements, both agreed not to challenge the seizure of $1.1 million on May 8 that year in Wyandotte, Oklahoma and the seizure of $38,000 from two bank accounts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] Janice Ayala joined Dowa Metals & Mining America as their Chief Compliance Officer on March 3, 2023.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] During Ayala's 27-year tenure at the Department of Homeland Security, her most recent role before joining Dowa was as Director of Joint Task Force – Investigations.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] This agency oversaw the investigation into both DG Auto Parts and Dowa.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] Jamison pleaded guilty sometime between the 2022 Oregon indictment and 2024, while Doyle's trial is set for October 29, 2024.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The three men involved in the shooting of Darren Almendarez were later charged with capital murder.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The District Attorney's office are seeking the death penalty for Joshua Stewart and Fredarius Clark, while Frederick Tardy, who was 17 at the time, was deemed too young.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The three were awaiting court dates in April 2024.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] A superseding indictment was unsealed on March 20, 2024, charging Tinu and Navin's mother, father and older brother, Anita, Nirmal and Michael Khanna respectively, with conspiracy to transport stolen catalytic converters from California to New Jersey.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The case alleged that, after Tinu and Navin were arrested, Anita, Nirmal and Michael continued buying and selling stolen catalytic converters under DG Auto Parts.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The case also alleged that they sold the PRP metals to employees of a New Jersey metal refinery, including Alfredo Mejia and Vishnu Chintaman, via a broker, Ricky Vega, and that they knew the catalytic converters that the metals came from were stolen.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] All of their cases remain pending as of July 2025.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] Tou Vang was sentenced to 12 years imprisonment on May 6, 2025.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] Navin Khanna pleaded guilty in the Northern District of Oaklahoma to one count of conspiracy to receive, possess, and transport of stolen goods over state lines and five counts of money laundering in July 2025.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] His case was transferred to the Eastern District of California, where he pleaded guilty to conspiracy to transport stolen property over state lines, conspiracy to commit promotional money laundering and interstate transportation of stolen property on February 27, 2026.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] His sentencing is, as of that date, unscheduled.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The case of Tinu Khanna remains pending as of July 2025.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] Tyler Curtis signed a plea agreement in October 2025, in which he admitted to conspiracy to commit money laundering.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] He was sentenced to 57 months federal imprisonment followed by three years supervised release on September 1, 2025.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] He also agreed to forfeit $3.4 million in cash, $212,000 in funds seized from bank accounts and two vehicles.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] His sentencing on state charges was scheduled for September 30.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] Rafael Davila operated a group which included Davila, Zachary Marshall, Santo Feliberty, Nicolas Davila, Carlos Fonseca, Alex Oyola and Torres.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The group targeted vehicles primarily in Massachusetts and New Hampshire between 2022 and April 2023.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] He was responsible for the planning of and transportation to each theft using a maroon Acura (which was later identified as both linking the thefts and belonging to Rafael Davila), the determining of the value of catalytic converters and the procurement of supplies.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] After the thefts, the catalytic converters would be sold to Jose Torres, who stored those he bought from several dealers and then sell them to recycling businesses.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] Torres would frequently sell the catalytic converters to Downpipe Depot and Recycling and DG Auto Parts, earning between $30,000 and $80,000 per week from them.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] At its end, the investigation expanded to include 78 law enforcement agencies overseen by the FBI and Massachusetts State Police.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] The group were arrested and charged in April 2023 with conspiracy to transport stolen property in interstate commerce, interstate transportation of stolen property, conspiracy to commit money laundering, conspiracy to commit bank theft and bank theft.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] As of February 2025, Fonseca, Oyola and Torres had also pleaded guilty and were awaiting sentencing, with Torres pleading guilty on May 17, 2023, and his sentencing scheduled for September 6 that year.
[src:catalytic-converter/2020-2022-catalytic-converter-theft-ring-p02] In the 18 months that followed the dismantling of the group, nine thefts of catalytic converters were reported.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters, soils, microbes, insects and aquatic life-forms.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In ecosystems, persistent acid rain negatively affects tree bark, leaving trees more susceptible to environmental stressors such as drought, fire, solar radiation, frost and pest infestation.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain is also capable of detrimenting soil composition by stripping it of nutrients such as calcium and magnesium which play a critical role in plant growth and maintaining healthy soil.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In terms of human infrastructure, acid rain also causes the peeling of paint, corrosion of steel structures, and weathering of stone buildings and statues as well as having impacts on human health.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Some governments, including those in Europe and North America, have made efforts since the 1970s to reduce the release of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide into the atmosphere through air pollution regulations such as the US Clean Air Act and the EU Ambient Air Quality Directive.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] These efforts have had positive results due to the widespread research on acid rain starting in the 1960s and the publicized information on its harmful effects.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The main source of sulfur and nitrogen compounds that result in acid rain are anthropogenic, but nitrogen oxides can also be produced naturally by lightning strikes and sulfur dioxide is produced by volcanic eruptions.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain is rain with a pH less than 5.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] A variety of natural and human-made sources contribute to the acidity of precipitations.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] For example nitric acid is produced by electric discharges in the atmosphere such as in lightnings.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The usual anthropogenic sources of acid deposition are sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] They react with water (as does carbon dioxide) to give solutions with pH < 5.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Occasional pH readings in rain and fog water of well below 2.4 have been reported in industrialized areas.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain was first systematically studied in Europe in the 1960s, in the United States and Canada in 1970s, and in India in the late 1980s.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The corrosive effect of polluted, acidic air of London on limestone and marble was noted in the 17th century by John Evelyn, who remarked upon the poor condition of the Arundel marbles.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Since the Industrial Revolution, emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides into the atmosphere have increased.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1852, Robert Angus Smith was the first to show the relationship between acid rain and atmospheric pollution in Manchester, England.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Smith coined the term "acid rain" in 1872.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] As soon as the 1960s, European scientists began widely observing and studying the phenomenon.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1955 two Swedish scientists had already quoted that "the precipitation over Sweden as a whole is definitely more acid than the CO2 equilibrium alone would permit".
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] At first, the main focus in this research laid on local effects of acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Waldemar Christofer Brøgger was the first to acknowledge long-distance transportation of pollutants crossing borders from the United Kingdom to Norway.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Near a century later this problem was systematically studied by Brynjulf Ottar in the 1970s.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Ottar's work was strongly influenced by Swedish soil scientist Svante Odén, who had drawn widespread attention to Europe's acid rain problem in popular newspapers and wrote a landmark paper on the subject in 1968.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The earliest report about acid rain in the United States came from chemical evidence gathered from Hubbard Brook Valley; public awareness of acid rain in the US increased in the 1970s after *The New York Times* reported on these findings.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1972, a group of scientists, including Gene Likens, discovered the rain that was deposited at White Mountains of New Hampshire was acidic.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The pH of the sample was measured to be 4.03 at Hubbard Brook.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The Hubbard Brook Ecosystem Study followed up with a series of research studies that analyzed the environmental effects of acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The alumina from soils neutralized acid rain that mixed with stream water at Hubbard Brook.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The result of this research indicated that the chemical reaction between acid rain and aluminium leads to an increasing rate of soil weathering.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Experimental research examined the effects of increased acidity in streams on ecological species.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1980, scientists modified the acidity of Norris Brook, New Hampshire, and observed the change in species' behaviors.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] There was a decrease in species diversity, an increase in community dominants, and a reduction in the food web complexity.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1980, the US Congress passed an Acid Deposition Act.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] This Act established an 18-year assessment and research program under the direction of the National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP).
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] NAPAP enlarged a network of monitoring sites to determine how acidic precipitation was, seeking to determine long-term trends, and established a network for dry deposition.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Using a statistically based sampling design, NAPAP quantified the effects of acid rain on a regional basis by targeting research and surveys to identify and quantify the impact of acid precipitation on freshwater and terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] NAPAP also assessed the effects of acid rain on historical buildings, monuments, and building materials.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] It also funded extensive studies on atmospheric processes and potential control programs.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] From the start, policy advocates from all sides attempted to influence NAPAP activities to support their particular policy advocacy efforts, or to disparage those of their opponents.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] For the US Government's scientific enterprise, a significant impact of NAPAP were lessons learned in the assessment process and in environmental research management to a relatively large group of scientists, program managers, and the public.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1981, the National Academy of Sciences was looking into research about the controversial issues regarding acid rain, in particular the role of fossil fuel combustion.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] President Ronald Reagan dismissed the issues of acid rain until his personal visit to Canada and confirmed that the Canadian border suffered from the drifting pollution from smokestacks originating in the US Midwest.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Reagan honored the agreement to Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau's enforcement of anti-pollution regulation.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1982, Reagan commissioned William Nierenberg to serve on the National Science Board.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Nierenberg selected scientists including Gene Likens to serve on a panel to draft a report on acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1983, the panel of scientists came up with a draft report, which concluded that acid rain is a real problem and solutions should be sought.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] White House Office of Science and Technology Policy reviewed the draft report and sent Fred Singer's suggestions of the report, which cast doubt on the anthropic causes of acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The panelists revealed rejections against Singer's positions and submitted the report to Nierenberg in April.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In May 1983, the House of Representatives voted against legislation controlling sulfur emissions.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] There was a debate about whether Nierenberg delayed the release of the report.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Nierenberg denied the saying about his suppression of the report and stated that it was withheld after the House's vote because it was not ready to be published.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1991, the US National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP) provided its first assessment of acid rain in the United States.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] It reported that 5% of New England lakes were acidic, with sulfates being the most common problem.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] They noted that 2% of the lakes could no longer support Brook Trout, and 6% of the lakes were unsuitable for the survival of many minnow species.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Subsequent *Reports to Congress* have documented chemical changes in soil and freshwater ecosystems, nitrogen saturation, soil nutrient decreases, episodic acidification, regional haze, and damage to historical monuments.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Meanwhile, in 1990, the US Congress passed a series of amendments to the Clean Air Act.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Title IV of these amendments established a cap and trade system designed to control emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Both these emissions proved to cause a significant problem for U.S. citizens and their access to healthy, clean air.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Title IV called for a total reduction of about 10 million tons of SO2 emissions from power plants, close to a 50% reduction.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Phase I began in 1995 and limited sulfur dioxide emissions from 110 of the largest power plants to 8.7 million tons of sulfur dioxide.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] One power plant in New England (Merrimack) was in Phase I.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Four other plants (Newington, Mount Tom, Brayton Point, and Salem Harbor) were added under other program provisions.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Phase II began in 2000 and affects most of the power plants in the country.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] On March 10, 2005, the EPA issued the Clean Air Interstate Rule (CAIR).
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] This rule provides states with a solution to the problem of power plant pollution that drifts from one state to another.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] CAIR will permanently cap emissions of SO2 and NOx in the eastern United States.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] CAIR hoped to reduce SO2 emissions in 28 eastern states and the District of Columbia by over 70% and NOx emissions by over 60% from 2003 levels.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] CAIR was replaced by the Cross-State Air Pollution Rule (CSAPR), as of 1 January 2015.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Overall, the program's cap and trade program has been successful in achieving its goals.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Since the 1990s, SO2 emissions have dropped 40%, and according to the Pacific Research Institute, acid rain levels have dropped 65% since 1976.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Conventional regulation was used in the European Union, which saw a decrease of over 70% in SO2 emissions during the same period.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 2007, total SO2 emissions were 8.9 million tons, achieving the program's long-term goal ahead of the 2010 statutory deadline.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 2007 the EPA estimated that by 2010, the overall costs of complying with the program for businesses and consumers would be $1 billion to $2 billion a year, only one-fourth of what was initially predicted.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Forbes says: "In 2010, by which time the cap and trade system had been augmented by the George W.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The term citizen science can be traced back as far as January 1989 to a campaign by the Audubon Society to measure acid rain, with 280 volunteers nationwide, all members of the Audubon Society, making a one-year commitment to collect and measure the pH of precipitation samples.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Canadian Harold Harvey was among the first to research a "dead" lake.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1972, he and Richard Beamish documented the gradual deterioration of fish stocks in 60 lakes in Killarney Park in Ontario, which they had been studying systematically since 1966.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In the 1970s and 80s, acid rain was a major topic of research at the Experimental Lakes Area (ELA) in Northwestern Ontario, Canada.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Researchers added sulfuric acid to whole lakes in controlled ecosystem experiments to simulate the effects of acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Because its remote conditions allowed for whole-ecosystem experiments, research at the ELA showed that the effect of acid rain on fish populations started at concentrations much lower than those observed in laboratory experiments.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In the context of a complete food web, fish populations crashed earlier than when acid rain had direct toxic effects to the fish because the acidity led to crashes in prey populations (e.g. mysids).
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] As experimental acid inputs were reduced, fish populations and lake ecosystems recovered at least partially, although invertebrate populations have still not completely returned to the baseline conditions.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] This research showed both that acidification was linked to declining fish populations and that the effects could be reversed if sulfuric acid emissions decreased, and influenced policy in Canada and the United States.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1985, seven Canadian provinces (all except British Columbia, Alberta, and Saskatchewan) and the federal government signed the Eastern Canada Acid Rain Program.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The provinces agreed to limit their combined sulfur dioxide emissions to 2.3 million tonnes by 1994.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The US-Canada Air Quality Agreement was signed in 1991.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 1998, all federal, provincial, and territorial Ministers of Energy and Environment signed The Canada-Wide Acid Rain Strategy for Post-2000, which was designed to protect lakes that are more sensitive than those protected by earlier policies.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain was first reported in Mumbai (then Bombay) in 1974.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain has been a reported cause of decrease in soil pH, especially in the northeast region, as well as the coastal regions of Karnataka, Kerala, Odisha, Bihar, and West Bengal.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The spread of acid rain over India was first studied by a team of researchers in 1989.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Increased risk might be posed by the expected rise in total sulphur emissions from 4,400 kilotonnes (kt) in 1990 to 6,500 kt in 2000, 10,900 kt in 2010 and 18,500 in 2020.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Damage to Taj Mahal is a popular example of acid rain's corrosive effect in India.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] India is the largest sulphur emitter, mostly from coal-fired power plants.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] On 11 July 2025, the Indian government changed its own rules, exempting most coal-fired power plants from installing technology to reduce sulphur dioxide (SO2) emissions, reversing a key environmental policy launched in 2015 to cut sulphur emissions.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In China, concern about the possible effects of acid rain emerged later than in Europe and North America.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The first reports in the international literature regarding acid rain in China appeared in the 1980s.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] A major cause of acid rain in China is the extensive use of coal, which in 2004 accounted for 69% of the energy production.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] However, a great need still exists for better monitoring of the environmental situation in China to support policy development and follow-up on emission reduction measures.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The most important gas which leads to acidification is sulfur dioxide.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] However, emissions of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and ammonia which are further oxidized to form nitric acid are of increasing importance due to stricter controls on emissions of sulfur compounds and the near absence of control on acid rain gasses emitted by intensive farming.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] 70 Tg(S) per year in the form of SO2 comes from fossil fuel combustion and industry, 2.8 Tg(S) from wildfires, and 7–8 Tg(S) per year from volcanoes.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The principal natural phenomena that contribute acid-producing gases to the atmosphere are emissions from volcanoes.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid-producing gases are also created by biological processes that occur in wetlands and the oceans.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The major biological source of atmospheric sulfur compounds is dimethyl sulfide.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Nitric acid is also produced by electrical activity in the atmosphere such as lightning.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Despite its toxicity, and negative effects of low pH, nitric acid in rainwater is an important source of fixed nitrogen for plant life.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acidic sulfate deposits associated with tephra have been detected in glacial ice thousands of years old in remote parts of the globe, suggesting that volcanism was the main agent of rain acidification before the Anthropocene.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The principal cause of present-day acid rain is sulfur and nitrogen compounds from human sources, such as coal-fired power stations, animal agriculture, fertilizers, steel mills, and motor vehicles.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Power plants account for a quarter of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and two-thirds of sulfur dioxide within the atmosphere.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Industrial acid rain is still a substantial problem in China and Russia and areas downwind from them.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] These areas all burn sulfur-containing coal to generate heat and electricity.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The problem of acid rain has not only increased with population and industrial growth, but has become more widespread.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The use of tall smokestacks to reduce local pollution has contributed to the spread of acid rain by releasing gases into regional atmospheric circulation; dispersal from these taller stacks causes pollutants to be carried farther, causing widespread ecological damage.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Often deposition occurs a considerable distance downwind of the emissions, with mountainous regions tending to receive the greatest deposition because of their higher rainfall and direct contact with long-distance transported clouds.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] An example of this effect is the low pH of rain which falls in Scandinavia.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain falls at a pH value of roughly 4, making it harmful to consume for humans, plants, microbes and animals.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] When these low pH levels fall in specific regions, they not only affect the environment but also human health.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] With acidic pH levels in humans comes hair loss, low urinary pH, severe mineral deficiency, constipation, and many cases of chronic disorders like fibromyalgia and basal-cell carcinoma.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Combustion of fuels and smelting of some ores produce sulfur dioxide and nitric oxides (NOx).
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] They are converted into sulfuric acid and nitric acid by photochemical reactions in the troposphere.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The detailed mechanisms depend on the presence water and traces of iron and manganese.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] A number of oxidants are capable of these reactions aside from O2, these include ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxygen.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Wet deposition of acids occurs when any form of precipitation (e.g. rain, snow, fog) removes acids from the atmosphere and delivers them to the Earth's surface.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] This can result from the deposition of acids produced in the raindrops or by the precipitation removing the acids either in clouds or below clouds.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Wet removal of both gases and aerosols are both of importance for wet deposition.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid deposition also occurs via dry deposition in the absence of precipitation.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] This can be responsible for as much as 20 to 60% of total acid deposition.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] This occurs when particles and gases stick to the ground, plants or other surfaces.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters and soils, killing terrestrial and aquatic life-forms as well as causing damage to buildings and having impacts on human health.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid and nitric acid have multiple impacts on aquatic ecosystems, including acidification, increased nitrogen and aluminium content, and alteration of biogeochemical processes.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Both the lower pH and higher aluminium concentrations in surface water that occur as a result of acid rain can cause damage to fish and other aquatic animals as well as to microbes and plants.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] At pH lower than 5 most fish eggs will not hatch and pH lower than 4 will kill adult fish.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] As lakes and rivers become more acidic, biodiversity is reduced, while it is less affected in regions where freshwater is naturally acid.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain has eliminated insect life and some fish species, including the brook trout in some lakes, streams, and creeks in geographically sensitive areas, such as the Adirondack Mountains of the United States.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] However, the extent to which acid rain contributes directly or indirectly via runoff from the catchment to lake and river acidity (i.e., depending on characteristics of the surrounding watershed) is variable.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The United States Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) website states: "Of the lakes and streams surveyed, acid rain caused acidity in 75% of the acidic lakes and about 50% of the acidic streams".
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Lakes hosted by silicate basement rocks are more acidic than lakes within limestone or other basement rocks with a carbonate composition (i.e. marble) due to buffering effects by carbonate minerals, even with the same amount of acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Soil biology and chemistry can be seriously damaged by acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Some microbes are unable to tolerate changes to low pH and are killed.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The enzymes of these microbes are denatured (changed in shape so they no longer function) by the acid, with attending collapse in soil functions (e.g. decomposition).
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The hydronium ions of acid rain also mobilize toxins, such as aluminium, and leach away essential nutrients and minerals such as magnesium.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Soil chemistry can be dramatically changed when base cations, such as calcium and magnesium, are leached by acid rain, thereby affecting sensitive tree species, such as sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*).
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Impacts of acidic water and soil acidification on plants could be minor or in most cases major.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Most minor cases which do not result in fatality of plant life can be attributed to the plants being less susceptible to acidic conditions and/or the acid rain being less potent.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] However, even in minor cases, the plant will eventually die due to the acidic water lowering the plant's natural pH.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acidic water enters the plant and causes important plant minerals to dissolve and get carried away; which ultimately causes the plant to die of lack of minerals for nutrition.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In major cases, which are more extreme, the same process of damage occurs as in minor cases, which is removal of essential minerals, but at a much quicker rate.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Likewise, acid rain that falls on soil and on plant leaves causes drying of the waxy leaf cuticle, which ultimately causes rapid water loss from the plant to the outside atmosphere and eventually results in death of the plant.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Soil acidification can lead to a decline in soil microbes as a result of a change in pH, which would have an adverse effect on plants due to their dependence on soil microbes to access nutrients.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] To see if a plant is being affected by soil acidification, one can closely observe the plant leaves.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] If the leaves are green and look healthy, the soil pH is normal and acceptable for plant life.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] But if the plant leaves have yellowing between the veins on their leaves, that means the plant is suffering from acidification and is unhealthy.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Moreover, a plant suffering from soil acidification cannot photosynthesize; the acid-water-induced process of drying out of the plant can destroy chloroplast organelles.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Without being able to photosynthesize, a plant cannot create nutrients for its own survival or oxygen for the survival of aerobic organisms, which affects most species on Earth and ultimately ends the purpose of the plant's existence.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] It has been suggested that the collapse of photosynthesis linked to acid rain (caused by the emission of sulfur oxide from intense volcanism) could have contributed to the Permian-Triassic mass extinction.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Adverse effects may be indirectly related to acid rain, like the acid's effects on soil (see above) or the high concentration of gaseous precursors to acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] High altitude forests are especially vulnerable as they are often surrounded by clouds and fog which are more acidic than rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Plants are capable of adapting to acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] On Jinyun Mountain, Chongqing, plant species were seen adapting to new environmental conditions.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The affects on the species ranged from being beneficial to detrimental.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] With natural rainfall or mild acid rainfall, the biochemical and physiological characteristics of plant seedlings were enhanced.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] However, once the pH decreases below the threshold of 3.5, the acid rain can no longer be beneficial and begins to have negative affects.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact photosynthesis in plant leaves, when leaves are exposed to a lower pH, photosynthesis is impacted due to the decline in chlorophyll.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain also has the ability to cause deformation to leaves at a cellular level, tissue scaring and changes to the stomatal, epidermis and mesophyll cells.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Additional impacts of acid rain includes a decline in cuticle thickness present on the leaf surface.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Because acid rain damages leaves, this directly impacts a plants ability to have a strong canopy cover, a decline in canopy cover can lead plants to be more vulnerable to diseases.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Dead or dying trees (forest dieback) often appear in areas impacted by acid rain, although other factors such as drought stress linked to global warming cannot be excluded, too.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain causes aluminium to leach from the soil, posing risks to both plant and animal life.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Furthermore, it strips the soil of critical minerals and nutrients necessary for tree growth.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] At higher altitudes, acidic fog and clouds can deplete nutrients from tree foliage, leading to discolored or dead leaves and needles, with broadleaved species tending to be more sentitive than conifers.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] This depletion compromises the trees' ability to absorb sunlight, weakening them and diminishing their capacity to endure cold conditions.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Other plants can also be damaged by acid rain, but the effect on food crops is (or should be) minimized by the application of lime and fertilizers to replace lost nutrients.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In cultivated areas, limestone may also be added to increase the ability of the soil to keep the pH stable through the buffering effect of calcium carbonate, but this tactic is largely unusable in the case of wilderness lands.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] When calcium is leached from the needles of red spruce, these trees become less cold tolerant and exhibit winter injury and even death.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain may also affect crop productivity by necrosis or changes to soil nutrients, which ultimately prevent plants from reaching maturity.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain has a much less harmful effect on oceans on a global scale, but it creates an amplified impact in the shallower waters of coastal waters.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain can cause the ocean's pH to fall, known as ocean acidification, making it more difficult for different coastal species to create their exoskeletons that they need to survive and escape predation.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] These coastal species link together as part of the ocean's food chain, and without them being a source for other marine life to feed off of, more marine life will die.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Coral's limestone skeleton is particularly sensitive to pH decreases, because the calcium carbonate, a core component of the limestone skeleton, dissolves in acidic (low pH) solutions.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In addition to acidification, excess nitrogen inputs from the atmosphere promote increased growth of phytoplankton and other marine plants, which, in turn, may cause more frequent harmful algal blooms and eutrophication (the creation of oxygen-depleted "dead zones") in some parts of the ocean.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] However, some studies on intertidal zones point to the prominence of acid rain as a cause of the observed decline in algal species richness.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact human health, especially when people breathe in particles released from acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The effects of acid rain on human health are complex and may be seen in several ways , such as respiratory issues for long-term exposure and indirect exposure through contaminated food and water sources.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Exposure to air pollutants associated with acid rain, such as nitrogen dioxide (NO2), may have a negative impact on respiratory health.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Water-soluble nitrogen dioxide accumulates in the tiny lung airways (bronchioles), where it is transformed into nitric and nitrous acids, causing damage to the cells of the respiratory tract by various mechanisms.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Pneumonia caused by nitric acids directly damages the epithelial cells lining the airways, resulting in pulmonary edema.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Exposure to nitrogen dioxide also reduces the immune response by inhibiting the generation of inflammatory cytokines by alveolar macrophages in response to bacterial infection, and more particularly in smokers.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The pollutant further reduces respiratory immunity by decreasing mucociliary clearance in the lower respiratory tract, which results in a reduced ability to remove respiratory infections.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The effects of sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid are similar because the former produces sulfuric acid when it comes into touch with the wet surfaces of your skin or respiratory system.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The amount of SO3 breath through the mouth is larger than the amount of SO3 breath through the nose.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] When humans breathe in sulfur trioxide, small droplets of sulfuric acid will form inside the body and enter the respiratory tract to the lungs depending on the particle size.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The effects of SO3 on the respiratory system lead to breathing difficulty in people who have asthma symptoms.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Sulfur trioxide also causes very corrosive and irritation on the skin, eye, and gastrointestinal tracts when there is direct exposure to a specific concentration or long-term exposure.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Consuming concentrated sulfuric acid has been known to burn the mouth and throat, erode a hole in the stomach, burns when it comes into contact with skin, make your eyes weep if it gets into them, and mortality.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] A 25 parts per million (ppm) maximum for nitrogen oxides (NOx) in working air has been set by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) for an 8-hour workday and a 40-hour workweek.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Additionally, OSHA has established a 5-ppm nitrogen dioxide exposure limit for 15 minutes in the workplace.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The not-to-exceed limits in the air, water, soil, or food that are recommended by US regulations are often based on levels that affect animals before being modified to assist in safeguarding people.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Depending on whether they employ different animal studies, have different exposure lengths (e.g., an 8-hour workday versus a 24-hour day), or for other reasons, these not-to-exceed values can vary between federal bodies.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The amount of sulfur dioxide that can be emitted into the atmosphere is capped by the EPA.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] This reduces the quantity of sulfur dioxide in the air that turns into sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid concentrations in workroom air are restricted by OSHA to 1 mg/m3.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Moreover, NIOSH advises a time-weighted average limit of 1 mg/m3.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain can damage buildings, historic monuments, and statues, especially those made of carbonate rocks, such as limestone and marble.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acids in the rain react with the calcium compounds in the stones to create gypsum, which then flakes off.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The effects of this are commonly seen on old gravestones, where acid rain can cause the inscriptions to become completely illegible.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Acid rain also increases the corrosion rate of metals, in particular iron, steel, copper and bronze.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Places significantly impacted by acid rain around the globe include most of eastern Europe from Poland northward into Scandinavia, the eastern third of the United States, and southeastern Canada.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Other affected areas include the southeastern coast of China and Taiwan.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Many coal-firing power stations use flue-gas desulfurization (FGD) to remove sulfur-containing gases from their stack gases.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] For a typical coal-fired power station, FGD will remove 95% or more of the SO2 in the flue gases.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] An example of FGD is the wet scrubber which is commonly used.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] A wet scrubber is basically a reaction tower equipped with a fan that extracts hot smoke stack gases from a power plant into the tower.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Lime or limestone in slurry form is also injected into the tower to mix with the stack gases and combine with the sulfur dioxide present.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The calcium carbonate of the limestone produces pH-neutral calcium sulfate that is physically removed from the scrubber.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] That is, the scrubber turns sulfur pollution into industrial sulfates.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In some areas the sulfates are sold to chemical companies as gypsum when the purity of calcium sulfate is high.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The effects of acid rain can last for generations, as the effects of pH level change can stimulate the continued leaching of undesirable chemicals into otherwise pristine water sources, killing off vulnerable insect and fish species and blocking efforts to restore native life.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Fluidized bed combustion also reduces the amount of sulfur emitted by power production.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Vehicle emissions control reduces emissions of nitrogen oxides from motor vehicles.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] International treaties on the long-range transport of atmospheric pollutants have been agreed upon by western countries for some time now.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Beginning in 1979, European countries convened in order to ratify general principles discussed during the UNECE Convention.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The purpose was to combat Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The 1985 Helsinki Protocol on the Reduction of Sulfur Emissions under the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution furthered the results of the convention.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Results of the treaty have already come to fruition, as evidenced by an approximate 40 percent drop in particulate matter in North America.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The effectiveness of the Convention in combatting acid rain has inspired further acts of international commitment to prevent the proliferation of particulate matter.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Canada and the US signed the Air Quality Agreement in 1991.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Most European countries and Canada signed the treaties.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Activity of the Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution Convention remained dormant after 1999, when 27 countries convened to further reduce the effects of acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 2000, foreign cooperation to prevent acid rain was sparked in Asia for the first time.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Ten diplomats from countries ranging throughout the continent convened to discuss ways to prevent acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Following these discussions, the Acid Deposition Monitoring Network in East Asia (EANET) was established in 2001 as an intergovernmental initiative to provide science-based inputs for decision makers and promote international cooperation on acid deposition in East Asia.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In 2023, the EANET member countries include Cambodia, China, Indonesia, Japan, Lao PDR, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Republic of Korea, Russia, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] In this regulatory scheme, every current polluting facility is given or may purchase on an open market an emissions allowance for each unit of a designated pollutant it emits.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] Operators can then install pollution control equipment, and sell portions of their emissions allowances they no longer need for their own operations, thereby recovering some of the capital cost of their investment in such equipment.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The intention is to give operators economic incentives to install pollution controls.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The first emissions trading market was established in the United States by enactment of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] The overall goal of the Acid Rain Program established by the Act is to achieve significant environmental and public health benefits through reductions in emissions of sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx), the primary causes of acid rain.
[src:catalytic-converter/acid-rain] To achieve this goal at the lowest cost to society, the program employs both regulatory and market based approaches for controlling air pollution.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] The parts, accessories, etc. for sale may or may not be manufactured by the OEM.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket encompasses parts for replacement, collision, appearance, and performance.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket provides a wide variety of parts of varying qualities and prices for nearly all vehicle makes and models.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] Consumers have the option of repairing their vehicles themselves (the "do-it-yourself" or "DIY" segment) or can take the vehicle to a professional repair facility (the "do-it-for me" or "DIFM" segment).
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket helps keep vehicles on the road by providing consumers the choice of where they want their vehicles serviced, maintained, or customized.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] The United States automotive aftermarket covering light-, medium- and heavy-duty vehicles is estimated to be worth $516 billion (2025).
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] The United States automotive aftermarket contribute more than 1.9% to GDP according to Hedges & Company.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] The aftermarket employs 4.9 million people who work at manufacturers, distributors, retailers and repair shops.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] In the United States, online sales of aftermarket accessories have increased year over year over traditional brick and mortar stores.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] In fact, according to Hedges & Company, "Total online eCommerce revenue for automotive parts and accessories in 2024 was at $42.4 billion in the US." That includes $21.7 billion from first-party 1P eCommerce websites and $20.7 billion from third-party 3P marketplaces.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] Singapore, which does not have a domestic automobile industry, is an especially important destination for businesses exporting automotive parts and accessories due to its high automobile turnover stemming from the peculiarities of its driving laws.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] High automobile turnover and the preference for new parts means that the market for remanufactured and reconditioned auto parts is very small.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] Combined with a high demand for "accessories, car-care products, prestige items, and new spare parts," Singapore's automotive aftermarket is large.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] In fact, Singapore has become a major automotive *components* manufacturing base, as several leading multinational corporations (MNCs) have established international procurement offices as well as their Southeast Asia distribution centers.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] In Canada, the automotive aftermarket is a C$19.4 billion industry that employs about 420,000 people.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] In Australia, the automotive aftermarket industry in 2013 was estimated to generate a AUD$5.2 billion turnover, with 21000 staff, and 1400 manufacturers.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] in Europe, the total volume of Independent Aftermarket (IAM) amounted to 127 billion Euros in 2015 (end-user prices without labor and tax).
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] At that moment there were 54 parts traders with annual turnover over 100 mio Euros in Europe, 6 of them exceeded 1 billion Euros.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] Meeting platform for the international automotive aftermarket is the B2B trade fair Automechanika Dubai which takes place every two years in Frankfurt.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] At last edition the hot topics were connected cars, autonomous driving, alternative drives and the workshop of the future.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] Among online retailers, Amazon.com and eBay Motors are the largest sellers of aftermarket parts and accessories in the U.S. by both units sold and revenue, and are expected to grow 25% in 2014, far outstripping traditional chain stores.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] As DIY parts sales soften at the retail counter, chain stores have pushed themselves into the DIFM commercial business, eating into distributors’ and wholesalers’ market share.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] Since 2007, DIY sales at the chain stores have fallen a total of 3% to 5%, while commercial sales have brought in a double-digit sales increase.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] AutoZone’s DIFM sales in 2013 alone increased over 13%.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] Online sales of auto parts and accessories in the United States, including 3P marketplaces, are estimated at $42.4 billion in 2024.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] Automobile manufacturers have attempted to hinder or suppress automotive aftermarket sales by means of copyright or patent infringement litigation.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] For example, in *British Leyland Motor Corp. v Armstrong Patents Co.* in the UK, the House of Lords decided in 1986 that Leyland could not claim copyright infringement in order to prevent the aftermarket sale of replacement tailpipes to purchasers of those motor cars.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] In 2005 Harley-Davidson filed a patent and trademark infringement lawsuit against two aftermarket engine manufacturers producing drop-in replacements for Harley's engines, namely S&S Cycle and Delkron, Inc.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] Harley accused S&S and Delkron of copying parts for Twin Cam engines and using Harley trademarks without permission.
[src:catalytic-converter/aftermarket-automotive] S&S argued that the suit was without any legal basis, and asserted that "a mutually beneficial relationship existed" between them and Harley.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:catalytic-converter/air-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:catalytic-converter/aw-additive] EP additives are used in applications such as gearboxes, while AW additives are used with lighter loads such as bushings.
[src:catalytic-converter/aw-additive] Some formulations use colloidal PTFE (Teflon), but its efficiency is controversial.
[src:catalytic-converter/aw-additive] Many AW additives function as EP additives, for example organophosphates or sulfur compounds.
[src:catalytic-converter/aw-additive] The mechanism of function of TCP and ZDDP is explained in EP additives.
[src:catalytic-converter/aw-additive] Under extreme pressure conditions, the performance of AW additives becomes insufficient and designated EP additives are required.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] A **catalytic converter** is an exhaust emission control device which converts toxic gases and pollutants in exhaust gas from an internal combustion engine into less-toxic pollutants by catalyzing a redox reaction.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters are usually used with internal combustion engines fueled by gasoline (petrol) or diesel, including lean-burn engines, and sometimes on kerosene heaters and stoves.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The first widespread introduction of catalytic converters was in the United States automobile market.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] To comply with the US Environmental Protection Agency's stricter regulation of exhaust emissions, most gasoline-powered vehicles starting with the 1975 model year are equipped with catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] These "two-way" oxidation converters combine oxygen with carbon monoxide (CO) and unburned hydrocarbons (HC) to produce carbon dioxide (CO2) and water (H2O).
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] "Three-way" converters, which also reduce oxides of nitrogen (NO*x*), were first commercialized by Volvo on the California-specification 1977 240 cars.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] When U.S. federal emission control regulations began requiring tight control of NOx for the 1981 model year, most all automakers met the tighter standards with three-way catalytic converters and associated engine control systems.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Oxidation-only two-way converters are still used on lean-burn engines to oxidize particulate matter and hydrocarbon emissions (including diesel engines, which typically use lean combustion), as three-way-converters require fuel-rich or stoichiometric combustion to successfully reduce NO*x*.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Although catalytic converters are most commonly applied to exhaust systems in automobiles, they are also used on electrical generators, forklifts, mining equipment, trucks, buses, locomotives, motorcycles, and on ships.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Rarely, devices similar to catalytic converters are used in appliances such as wood stoves to control emissions.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converter prototypes were first designed in France at the end of the 19th century, when only a few thousand "oil cars" were on the roads; these prototypes had inert clay-based materials coated with platinum, rhodium, and palladium and sealed into a double metallic cylinder.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] A few decades later, a catalytic converter was patented by Eugene Houdry, a French mechanical engineer.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Houdry was an expert in catalytic oil refining, having invented the catalytic cracking process that all modern refining is based on today.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Houdry moved to the United States in 1930 to live near the refineries in Philadelphia and develop his catalytic refining process.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] When the results of early studies of smog in Los Angeles were published, Houdry became concerned about the role of smokestack exhaust and automobile exhaust in air pollution and founded a company called Oxy-Catalyst.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Houdry first developed catalytic converters for smokestacks, and later developed catalytic converters for warehouse forklifts running on unleaded gasoline.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In the mid-1950s, he began research to develop catalytic converters for gasoline engines used on cars and was awarded United States Patent 2,742,437 for his work.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters were further developed by a series of engineers including Carl D.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Mooney, Antonio Eleazar, and Phillip Messina at Engelhard Corporation, creating the first production catalytic converter in 1973.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Environmental Protection Agency's new exhaust emissions regulations, most gasoline-powered vehicles manufactured from 1975 onwards are equipped with catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Early catalytic converters were "two-way", combining oxygen with carbon monoxide (CO) and unburned hydrocarbons (HC, chemical compounds in fuel of the form CmHn) to produce carbon dioxide (CO2) and water (H2O).
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] These stringent emission control regulations also resulted in the removal of the antiknock agent tetraethyl lead from automotive gasoline, to reduce lead in the air.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Lead and its compounds are catalyst poisons and foul catalytic converters by coating the catalyst's surface.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Requiring the removal of lead allowed the use of catalytic converters to meet the other emission standards in the regulations.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] To lower harmful NO*x* emissions, a twin-catalyst system was developed in the 1970s – this added a separate (rhodium/platinum) catalyst which reduced NO*x* ahead of the air pump, after which a two-way catalytic converter (palladium/platinum) removed HC and CO.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] This cumbersome and expensive system was soon made redundant, after it was noted that under some conditions the initial catalyst also removed HC and CO.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] This led to the development of the three-way catalyst, made possible by electronics and engine management developments.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Pfefferle developed a catalytic combustor for gas turbines in the early 1970s, allowing combustion without significant formation of nitrogen oxides and carbon monoxide.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Four-way catalytic converters have also been developed which also remove particulates from engine exhaust; since most of these particulates are unburned hydrocarbons, they can be burned to convert them into carbon dioxide.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] A washcoat is a carrier for the catalytic materials and is used to disperse the materials over a large surface area.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Aluminum oxide, titanium dioxide, silicon dioxide e.g. colloidal silica or a mixture of silica and alumina can be used.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The catalytic materials are suspended in the washcoat prior to applying to the core.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Washcoat materials are selected to form a rough, irregular surface, which increases the surface area compared to the smooth surface of the bare substrate.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] These oxides are mainly added as oxygen storage promoters.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The catalyst itself is most often a mix of precious metals, mostly from the platinum group.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Platinum is the most active catalyst and is widely used, but is not suitable for all applications because of unwanted additional reactions and historically high cost.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Palladium and rhodium are two other precious metals used, though as of February 2023, platinum has become the least expensive of the platinum group metals.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Rhodium is used as a reduction catalyst, palladium is used as an oxidation catalyst, and platinum is used both for reduction and oxidation.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Cerium, iron, manganese, and nickel are also used, although each has limitations.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Copper can also be used in most countries.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Nickel is not legal for use in the European Union because of its reaction with carbon monoxide into toxic nickel tetracarbonyl.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Upon failure, a catalytic converter can be recycled rather than being scrapped.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The precious metals inside the converter – the platinum, palladium, and rhodium – are extracted.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters require a temperature of 400 °C (750 °F) to operate effectively.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Therefore, they are placed as close to the engine as possible, or one or more smaller catalytic converters (known as "pre-cats") are placed immediately after the exhaust manifold.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The two-way catalytic converter is widely used on diesel engines to reduce hydrocarbon and carbon monoxide emissions.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] They were also used on gasoline engines in American and Canadian automobile markets until 1981.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Because of their inability to control oxides of nitrogen, manufacturers briefly installed twin catalyst systems, with an NO*x* reducing, rhodium/platinum catalyst ahead of the air pump, which led to the development of the three-way catalytic converter.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The two-way catalytic converter also continued to be used on certain, lower-cost cars in some markets such as Europe, where NO*x* emissions were not universally regulated until the introduction of the Euro 3 emissions standard in 2000.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The three-way catalytic converters have the additional advantage of controlling the emission of nitric oxide (NO) and nitrogen dioxide (NO2) (both together abbreviated with NO*x* and not to be confused with nitrous oxide (N2O)).
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] NO*x* are precursors to acid rain and smog.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The reduction and oxidation catalysts are typically contained in a common housing; however, in some instances, they may be housed separately.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] These three reactions occur most efficiently when the engine runs within a narrow band of air-fuel ratios near the stoichiometric point.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Total conversion efficiency falls very rapidly when the engine is operated outside of this band.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Slightly lean of stoichiometric, the exhaust gases from the engine contain excess oxygen, the production of NO*x* by the engine increases, and the efficiency of the catalyst at reducing NO*x* falls off rapidly.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] However, the conversion of HC and CO is very efficient due to the available oxygen, oxidizing to H2O and CO2.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Slightly rich of stoichiometric, the production of CO and unburnt HC by the engine starts to increase dramatically, available oxygen decreases, and the efficiency of the catalyst for oxidizing CO and HC decreases significantly, especially as stored oxygen becomes depleted.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] However, the efficiency of the catalyst at reducing NO*x* is good, and the production of NO*x* by the engine decreases.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] To maintain catalyst efficiency, the air–fuel ratio must stay close to stoichiometric and not remain rich or lean for too long.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Therefore, engines fitted with regulated 3-way catalytic converters have a closed-loop feedback carburetor or fuel injection engine control system to manage a continuous rich-lean balance required for effective NO*x* reduction and HC+CO oxidation.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The control system allows the catalyst to release oxygen during slightly rich operating conditions, which oxidizes CO and HC under conditions that also favor the reduction of NOx.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Before the stored oxygen is depleted, the control system shifts the air-fuel ratio to become slightly lean, improving HC and CO oxidation while storing additional oxygen in the catalyst material, at a small penalty in NO*x* reduction efficiency.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Then the air–fuel mixture is brought back to slightly rich, at a small penalty in CO and HC oxidation efficiency, and the cycle repeats.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Efficiency is improved when this oscillation around the stoichiometric point is small and carefully controlled.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Closed-loop control under light to moderate load is accomplished by using one or more oxygen sensors in the exhaust system.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] When oxygen is detected by the sensor, the air-fuel ratio is lean of stoichiometric, and when oxygen is not detected, it is rich.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The control system adjusts the amount of fuel being fed to the engine based on this signal to keep the air-fuel ratio near the stoichiometric point in order to maximize the catalyst conversion efficiency.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The control algorithm is also affected by the time delay between the adjustment of the fuel flow rate and the sensing of the changed air–fuel ratio by the sensor, as well as the sigmoidal response of the oxygen sensors.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Typical control systems are designed to rapidly sweep the air–fuel ratio such that it oscillates slightly around the stoichiometric point, staying near the optimal efficiency point while managing the levels of stored oxygen and unburnt HC.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Closed-loop control is often suspended during high load/maximum power operation, when an increase in emissions is permitted and a rich mixture is commanded to increase power and prevent exhaust gas temperature from exceeding design limits.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] This presents a challenge for control system and catalyst design.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] During such operations, large amounts of unburnt HC are produced by the engine, well beyond the capacity of the catalyst to release oxygen.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The surface of the catalyst quickly becomes saturated with HC.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] When returning to lower power output and leaner air-fuel ratios, the control system must prevent excessive oxygen from reaching the catalyst too quickly, as this will rapidly burn the HC in the already hot catalyst, potentially exceeding the design temperature limit of the catalyst.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Excessive catalyst temperature can prematurely age the catalyst, reducing its efficiency before reaching its design lifetime.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Excessive catalyst temperature can also be caused by cylinder misfire, which continuously flows unburnt HC combined with oxygen to the hot catalyst, burning in the catalyst and increasing its temperature.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Unwanted reactions result in the formation of hydrogen sulfide and ammonia, which poison catalysts.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Nickel or manganese is sometimes added to the washcoat to limit hydrogen-sulfide emissions.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Sulfur-free or low-sulfur fuels eliminate or minimize problems with hydrogen sulfide.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] For compression-ignition (i.e., diesel) engines, the most commonly used catalytic converter is the *diesel oxidation catalyst* (DOC).
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] DOCs contain palladium or platinum supported on alumina.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] This catalyst converts particulate matter (PM), hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide to carbon dioxide and water.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] These converters often operate at 90 percent efficiency, virtually eliminating diesel odor and helping reduce visible particulates.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] These catalysts are ineffective for NO*x*, so NO*x* emissions from diesel engines are controlled by exhaust gas recirculation (EGR).
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In 2010, most light-duty diesel manufacturers in the U.S. added catalytic systems to their vehicles to meet federal emissions requirements.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Two techniques have been developed for the catalytic reduction of NO*x* emissions under lean exhaust conditions, selective catalytic reduction (SCR) and the NO*x* adsorber.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Instead of precious metal-containing NO*x* absorbers, most manufacturers selected base-metal SCR systems that use a reagent such as ammonia to reduce the NO*x* into nitrogen and water.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Ammonia is supplied to the catalyst system by the injection of urea into the exhaust, which then undergoes thermal decomposition and hydrolysis into ammonia.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The urea solution is also referred to as diesel exhaust fluid (DEF).
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Diesel exhaust contains relatively high levels of particulate matter.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters remove only 20–40% of PM so particulates are cleaned up by a soot trap or diesel particulate filter (DPF).
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In the U.S., all on-road light, medium, and heavy-duty diesel-powered vehicles built after 1 January 2007, are subject to diesel particulate emission limits, and so are equipped with a 2-way catalytic converter and a diesel particulate filter.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] As long as the engine was manufactured before 1 January 2007, the vehicle is not required to have the DPF system.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] This led to an inventory runup by engine manufacturers in late 2006 so they could continue selling pre-DPF vehicles well into 2007.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] For lean-burn spark-ignition engines, an oxidation catalyst is used in the same manner as in a diesel engine.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Emissions from lean burn spark ignition engines are very similar to emissions from a diesel compression ignition engine.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Many vehicles have a close-coupled catalytic converter located near the engine's exhaust manifold.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The converter heats up quickly, due to its exposure to the very hot exhaust gases, allowing it to reduce undesirable emissions during the engine warm-up period.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] This is achieved by burning off the excess hydrocarbons which result from the extra-rich mixture required for a cold start.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] When catalytic converters were first introduced, most vehicles used carburetors that provided a relatively rich air-fuel ratio.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Oxygen (O2) levels in the exhaust stream were therefore generally insufficient for the catalytic reaction to occur efficiently.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Most designs of the time therefore included secondary air injection, which injected air into the exhaust stream.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] This increased the available oxygen, allowing the catalyst to function as intended.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Some three-way catalytic converter systems have air injection systems with the air injected between the first (NO*x* reduction) and second (HC and CO oxidation) stages of the converter.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] As in two-way converters, this injected air provides oxygen for the oxidation reactions.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] An upstream air injection point, ahead of the catalytic converter, is also sometimes present to provide additional oxygen only during the engine warm up period.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] This causes unburned fuel to ignite in the exhaust tract, thereby preventing it reaching the catalytic converter at all.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] This technique reduces the engine runtime needed for the catalytic converter to reach its "light-off" or operating temperature.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Most newer vehicles have electronic fuel injection systems, and do not require air injection systems in their exhausts.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Instead, they provide a precisely controlled air-fuel mixture that quickly and continually cycles between lean and rich combustion.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Catalyst poisoning occurs when the catalytic converter is exposed to exhaust containing substances that coat the working surfaces, so that they cannot contact and react with the exhaust.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The most notable contaminant is lead, so vehicles equipped with catalytic converters can run only on unleaded fuel.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Other common catalyst poisons include sulfur, manganese (originating primarily from the gasoline additive MMT), and silicon, which can enter the exhaust stream if the engine has a leak that allows coolant into the combustion chamber.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Phosphorus is another catalyst contaminant.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Although phosphorus is no longer used in gasoline, it (and zinc, another low-level catalyst contaminant) was widely used in engine oil antiwear additives such as zinc dithiophosphate (ZDDP).
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Beginning in 2004, a limit of phosphorus concentration in engine oils was adopted in the API SM and ILSAC GF-4 specifications.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Depending on the contaminant, catalyst poisoning can sometimes be reversed by running the engine under a very heavy load for an extended period of time.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The increased exhaust temperature can sometimes vaporize or sublimate the contaminant, removing it from the catalytic surface.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] However, removal of lead deposits in this manner is usually not possible because of lead's high boiling point.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Oil and coolant leaks, perhaps caused by a head gasket leak, can also cause high unburned hydrocarbons.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Emissions regulations vary considerably from jurisdiction to jurisdiction.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Most automobile spark-ignition engines in North America have been fitted with catalytic converters since 1975, and the technology used in non-automotive applications is generally based on automotive technology.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In many jurisdictions, it is illegal to remove or disable a catalytic converter for any reason other than its direct and immediate replacement.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Nevertheless, some vehicle owners remove or "gut" the catalytic converter on their vehicle.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In such cases, the converter may be replaced by a welded-in section of ordinary pipe or a flanged "test pipe", ostensibly meant to check if the converter is clogged by comparing how the engine runs with and without the converter.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] This facilitates temporary reinstallation of the converter in order to pass an emission test.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Vehicles without functioning catalytic converters generally fail emission inspections.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The automotive aftermarket supplies high-flow converters for vehicles with upgraded engines, or whose owners prefer an exhaust system with larger-than-stock capacity.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters have been mandatory on all new gasoline cars sold in the European Union and the United Kingdom since 1 January 1993 in order to comply with the Euro 1 emission standards.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Faulty catalytic converters as well as undamaged early types of converters can restrict the flow of exhaust, which negatively affects vehicle performance and fuel economy.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Modern catalytic converters do not significantly restrict exhaust flow.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] A 2006 test on a 1999 Honda Civic, for example, showed that removing the stock catalytic converter netted only a 3% increase in maximum horsepower; a new metallic core converter only cost the car 1% horsepower, compared to no converter.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Carburetors on pre-1981 vehicles without feedback fuel-air mixture control could easily provide too much fuel to the engine, which could cause the catalytic converter to overheat and potentially ignite flammable materials under the car.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Vehicles fitted with catalytic converters emit most of their total pollution during the first five minutes of engine operation; that is, before the catalytic converter has warmed up sufficiently to be fully effective.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In the early 2000s it became common to place the catalyst converter right next to the exhaust manifold, close to the engine, for much quicker warm-up.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In 1995, Alpina introduced an electrically heated catalyst.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Called "E-KAT", it was used in Alpina's B12 5,7 E-KAT based on the BMW 750i.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Heating coils inside the catalytic converter assemblies are electrified just after the engine is started, bringing the catalyst up to operating temperature very quickly to qualify the vehicle for low emission vehicle (LEV) designation.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] BMW later introduced the same heated catalyst, developed jointly by Emitec, Alpina, and BMW, in its 750i in 1999.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Some vehicles contain a pre-cat, a small catalytic converter upstream of the main catalytic converter which heats up faster on vehicle start up, reducing the emissions associated with cold starts.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] A pre-cat is most commonly used by an auto manufacturer when trying to attain the Ultra Low Emissions Vehicle (ULEV) rating, such as on the Toyota MR2 Roadster.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters have proven to be reliable and effective in reducing noxious tailpipe emissions.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Because of the external location and the use of valuable precious metals including platinum, palladium and rhodium, catalytic converters are a target for thieves.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The problem is especially common among late-model pickup trucks and truck-based SUVs, because of their high ground clearance and easily removed bolt-on catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Welded-on converters are also at risk of theft, as they can be easily cut off.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Pipecutters are often used to quietly remove the converter but other tools such as a portable reciprocating saw can damage other components of the car, such as the oxygen sensor, wiring or fuel lines, with potentially dangerous consequences.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In 2023, bipartisan legislation to combat catalytic converter theft was introduced in the U.S.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The Preventing Auto Recycling Thefts Act (PART Act) would mandate catalytic converters in new vehicles to come with traceable identification numbers.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Additionally, the legislation would make catalytic converter theft a federal criminal offense.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Rising metal prices in the U.S. during the 2000s commodities boom led to a significant increase in converter theft.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] A catalytic converter can cost more than $1,000 to replace, more if the vehicle is damaged during the theft.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Apart from damaging other systems of the vehicle, theft can also cause death and injury to thieves.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Thefts of catalytic converters rose over tenfold in the United States from the late 2010s to early 2020s, driven presumably by the rise in the price of precious metals contained within the converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Study findings reveal an average price elasticity of 1.98, which means that a 10 percent increase in the price of metal leads to an approximate 20 percent increase in thefts.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] According to the National Insurance Crime Bureau, there were 1,298 reported cases of catalytic converter theft in 2018, which increased to 14,433 in 2020.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In 2022, it was reported that the number of catalytic converter thefts in the United States sharply rose to 153,000 total thefts for the year.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] From 2019 to 2020, thieves in the United Kingdom were targeting older-model hybrid cars (such as Toyota's hybrids) which have more precious metals than newer vehicles—sometimes worth more than the value of the car—leading to scarcity and long delays in replacing them.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In 2021 a trend emerged in the Democratic Republic of the Congo where catalytic converters were alleged to be stolen for use in illicit street drug production.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The drug, a powder known as "bombé," was said to be a mixture of powdered pills/vitamins and pulverized honeycomb structures of catalytic converters.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In 2023, however, a study of various samples of the drug concluded that its alleged origin from catalytic exhausts was found to be unsubstantiated.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Various jurisdictions now require on-board diagnostics to monitor the function and condition of the emissions-control system, including the catalytic converter.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Vehicles equipped with OBD-II diagnostic systems are designed to alert the driver to a misfire condition by means of illuminating the "check engine" light on the dashboard, or flashing it if the current misfire conditions are severe enough to potentially damage the catalytic converter.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] On-board diagnostic systems take several forms.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Temperature sensors are used for two purposes.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The first is as a warning system, typically on two-way catalytic converters such as those used on LPG forklifts.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The function of the sensor is to warn of catalytic converter temperature above the safe limit of 750 °C (1,380 °F).
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Modern catalytic-converter designs are not as susceptible to temperature damage and can withstand sustained temperatures of 900 °C (1,650 °F).
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Temperature sensors are also used to monitor catalyst functioning: usually two sensors will be fitted, with one before the catalyst and one after to monitor the temperature rise over the catalytic-converter core.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The oxygen sensor is the basis of the closed-loop control system on a spark-ignited rich-burn engine; however, it is also used for diagnostics.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] In vehicles with OBD II, a second oxygen sensor is fitted after the catalytic converter to monitor the O2 levels.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The O2 levels are monitored to see the efficiency of the burn process.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The on-board computer makes comparisons between the readings of the two sensors.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] The readings are taken by voltage measurements.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] If both sensors show the same output or the rear O2 is "switching", the computer recognizes that the catalytic converter either is not functioning or has been removed, and will operate a malfunction indicator lamp and affect engine performance.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Simple "oxygen sensor simulators" have been developed to circumvent this problem by simulating the change across the catalytic converter with plans and pre-assembled devices available on the Internet.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Although these are not legal for on-road use, they have been used with mixed results.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] Similar devices apply an offset to the sensor signals, allowing the engine to run a more fuel-economical lean burn that may, however, damage the engine or the catalytic converter.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] NO*x* sensors are extremely expensive and are in general used only when a compression-ignition engine is fitted with a selective catalytic-reduction (SCR) converter, or a NO*x* absorber in a feedback system.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] When fitted to an SCR system, there may be one or two sensors.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] When one sensor is fitted it will be pre-catalyst; when two are fitted, the second one will be post-catalyst.
[src:catalytic-converter/catalytic-converter] They are used for the same reasons and in the same manner as an oxygen sensor; the only difference is the substance being monitored.
